{{Infobox person |name = Rosalyn Koo |image = |alt = |caption = |birth_name = Rosalyn Chin-Ming Chen |birth_date = 1929 |birth_place = [[Shanghai]], [[China]] |death_date = |death_place = |spouse = |nationality = American |other_names = Rosalyn Chin-Ming Koo |occupation = Architectural firm manager and philanthropist |years_active = 1973-present |notable_works = }} '''Rosalyn Koo''' (born 1929) served as Executive Vice President of MBT Associates, an architectural firm listed in the 1980s as one of the 500 fastest-growing private companies in America, for 30 years. After her retirement, Koo turned to philanthropy and social activism. She has served in non-profits which assist senior citizens, such as Self-Help for the Elderly, in California, and those which assist girls trying to attain an education in China, through such organizations as [[The 1990 Institute]] and the [[All-China Women's Federation]]. Koo has been the recipient of numerous honors and was inducted into the Women's Hall of Fame in 2007.
==Biography== Rosalyn Chin-Ming Chen{{sfn|University of California, Berkeley|1953|p=40}} was born in 1929 in [[Shanghai]], [[China]]<ref name=schools>{{cite news|last1=Roberts|first1=Lindsey M.|title=Pro Bono: Village Green|url=http://www.architectmagazine.com/practice/pro-bono/pro-bono-village-green_o|accessdate=7 October 2015|publisher=Architect Magazine|date=2 May 2011|location=Washington, DC}}</ref> After completing her studies at [[Shanghai No. 3 Girls' High School|McTyeire School]], Chen moved to the United States in 1947 to attend [[Mills College]].{{sfn|Wheeler|2012|p=54}} She transferred to [[UC Berkeley]]<ref name=schooling>{{cite web|title=Rosalyn Koo|url=http://www.1990institute.org/assets/Rosalyn-Koo.pdf|publisher=1990 Institute|accessdate=7 October 2015|location=San Francisco, California}}</ref> and earned a degree in economics in 1953.{{sfn|University of California, Berkeley|1953|p=40}} By 1957, when she attained her permanent residency, Chen was married.<ref name="H. Con. Res. 89">{{cite web|title=Granting of Permanent Residence to Certain Aliens|website=US House of Representatives|publisher=Government Printing Office|accessdate=7 October 2015|location=Washington, DC|page=B16|date=24 May 1957|quote=Chen (Koo), Rosalyn Chin-Ming}}</ref>
In 1958,<ref name=schooling/> Koo joined the architectural firm MBT Associates in the San Francisco Bay area, which had been founded in 1954.<ref name="Perkins+Will Acquires MBT">{{cite web|title=Perkins+Will Acquires MBT Architecture|url=http://california.construction.com/news/openings/archive/0601.asp|publisher=California Construction|accessdate=8 October 2015|location=San Francisco, California|date=January 2006}}</ref> She served as Chief Financial Officer and was the only principal of the firm who was not an architect. The firm specialized in building commercial and university research and laboratory projects. In 1983, the firm was listed as one of the 500 fastest growing firms in the US by ''[[Inc. (magazine)|Inc.]]'' Magazine in spite of an overall industry downward trend of nearly 33% according to the [[American Institute of Architects]].<ref name=Inc.>{{cite news|last1=Delano|first1=Sara|title=But Will They Still Love Your Tomorrow?|url=http://www.inc.com/magazine/19840101/2630.html|accessdate=7 October 2015|publisher=Inc. Magazine|date=1 January 1984|location=New York City NY}}</ref> Among the many clients served were [[Allergan]], [[Genentech]], [[Merck & Co.|Merck]], Stanford University, [[UC-San Diego]], [[UC San Francisco]], the [[University of Virginia]], and the [[University of Washington]]<ref name="Perkins+Will Acquires MBT"/> with numerous award-winning projects, like the Beckman Center for Molecular & Genetic Medicine at [[Stanford University]], the Genencor International Technology Center in [[Palo Alto, California]], and the Technical Headquarters Lab Building E of [[Chevron Corporation|Chevron Research Company]] in Richmond, California.<ref name="Award winning labs">{{cite web|title=R&D Magazine's Laboratory of the Year Winners|url=http://www.rdmag.com/articles/2014/03/r-d-magazines-laboratory-year-winners|publisher=R&D Magazine|accessdate=8 October 2015|date=23 March 2014}}</ref> After 30 years at MBT, Koo retired in 1988.<ref name=schooling/>
In 1978, Koo returned to China for the first time and made contact with a former principal at her alma mater, then known as Shanghai Public High School No. 3. Koo committed that overseas investors would be found if the principal could convince the government to return the school to an all-girls facility. By 1984, the school had been restored to a girls school and an overseas alumni association was providing funding for new science laboratories.{{sfn|Wheeler|2012|p=54}} She soon joined her efforts with financing programs offered by [[The 1990 Institute]] and pledged to help 1,000 girls finish primary school.{{sfn|Wheeler|2012|p=103}} In 2000, Koo toured western China visiting the provinces of Gansu, [[Shanxi]] and Shaanxi. Upon her return, she and Institute partners began a Dragon Fund to help educate girls in western China. The initial three projects were a Women’s and Children’s Training Center in [[Gansu]], a greenhouse in Zhang Xian, and the "Spring Bud" scholarship program to provide funds for elementary school of girls in [[Shaanxi]] Province. Koo returned each year to measure the girls' progress and soon extended the scholarship funds to secondary schooling.{{sfn|Wheeler|2012|p=67}} In 2008, after the [[2008 Sichuan Province earthquake|earthquake in Sichuan Province]], Koo extended her commitment to including girls in Sichuan Province as well. Since their school buildings had been destroyed, Koo partnered with Jennifer Devlin of [[EHDD]] in San Francisco, to build a seismically safe school to replace three which had been damaged by the quake. Working with local partners they built the school and provided input for new Chinese construction and seismic codes to ensure safety.<ref name=schools/> As of 2012, with Koo's annual visit, she had assisted over 1000 girls in the Shaanxi province and 168 of them had gone on to university studies.<ref name="still visiting China">{{cite news|last1=Wenjun|first1=Fan|title=ACWF Leaders Meet with 1990 Institute Founder Rosalyn Koo|url=http://www.womenofchina.cn/womenofchina/html1/news/leaders/14/6032-1.htm|accessdate=8 October 2015|publisher=Women of China|date=23 October 2012|location=Beijing, China}}</ref>
In 1986, she joined the board of a San Francisco-based program called "Self Help for the Elderly" and assisted the organization with planning and financing strategies<ref name="Self-Help for elderly">{{cite web|title=Tribute to Legends|url=http://www.selfhelpelderly.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/40-tribute.pdf|publisher=Self Help for the Elderly|accessdate=7 October 2015|location=San Francisco CA|date=2006}}</ref> to expand their services. Primarily, the organization serves seniors of Asian heritage and provides language courses, meals, and services to help their clients maintain their independence and well-being.<ref name=Well-being>{{cite news|last1=Weigel|first1=Samantha|title=San Mateo's Self-Help for the Elderly may need new home|url=http://www.smdailyjournal.com/articles/lnews/2015-02-23/san-mateos-self-help-for-the-elderly-may-need-new-home/1776425138847.html|accessdate=7 October 2015|publisher=Daily Journal|date=23 February 2015|location=San Mateo CA}}</ref> In 2007, Koo was inducted into the Women's Hall of Fame for her contributions to sustainable living.<ref name="Hall of Fame">{{cite news|title=14 to join Women's Hall of Fame|url=http://www.insidebayarea.com/sanmateocountytimes/localnews/ci_5287887|accessdate=8 October 2015|publisher=Inside Bay Area|date=23 February 2007|location=San Mateo CA}}</ref> By 2015 the organization had 12 activity centers and Koo was the chair of the organization. She was advocating for the City of San Mateo to develop a center for the 1000 senior citizens who would be affected by closure of their current facility.<ref name=Well-being/>
